article.description:
La Toya Thomas scored 16 points to help the
San Antonio Silver Stars beat Seattle 75-65 on Thursday night as
the Storm played without All-Star center Lauren Jackson.
article.headline: Storm's No. 3 seed in jeopardy after loss to Silver Stars
article.linkText: Storm's No. 3 seed in jeopardy after loss to Silver Stars
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- With a playoff appearance already set, the
Seattle Storm gave All-Star center Lauren Jackson a break. The San
Antonio Silver Stars took advantage of her absence.

La Toya Thomas scored 16 points to help the Silver Stars beat
Seattle 75-65 on Thursday night as Jackson sat on the bench in
street clothes resting a sore left foot.

The Silver Stars (13-20) ended a season-high six-game losing
streak and snapped the Storm's four-game winning streak.

"We're out of the playoffs, but we're still trying to win and
build this team," Thomas said. "It was a good night for me."

Thomas, who missed 15 games earlier this season with a knee
injury, came off the bench and was 8-for-10 from the floor.

Seattle (18-15) already has earned a playoff spot, but the Storm
will have to defeat Houston in their regular season finale Saturday
to hold down the third spot.

Los Angeles will be the top seed in the West and will play
Seattle if the Storm finishes fourth. Seattle will play No. 2 seed
Sacramento if the Storm is third.

Storm coach Anne Donovan isn't worried about the playoff
pairing, so she said Jackson may also miss the game Saturday in
Houston.

"It doesn't really matter who we play," Donovan said. "I just
hope we can snap back and end the season on a winning note. We were
very sluggish tonight."

The Storm committed 19 turnovers, which led to 30 points for San
Antonio. Point guard Sue Bird finished the game with no assists.

Jackson missed her third game of the season -- her first since
July 18.

She was replaced in the lineup by Tiffani Johnson, who scored
four points on 2-of-7 shooting.

Betty Lennox had 17 points for Seattle, which shot 28-for-70
from the floor.

The Silver Stars, who got 15 points each from Agnieszka
Bibrzycka and Vickie Johnson, led by 14 points with 2:50 remaining
in the third quarter.

Johnson also dished out three assists for the Silver Stars,
which put her past 900 for her career. She's sixth all time in the
WNBA.

The Storm cut the lead to 63-60 with 4:44 left in the game. But
the Silver Stars ended the game by outscoring the Storm 12-5.

Seattle had won a franchise-record five straight road games. The
Storm struggled through a 37-percent shooting performance in the
first half. The Storm were 1-for-9 from the field during a span of
5:47 late in the second quarter when the Silver Stars outscored
Seattle 13-2 to go up by nine points.

The Storm also committed five of their 10 first-half turnovers
during the San Antonio run, but they made both of their shots
during the final minute to cut the San Antonio lead to 33-28 at
halftime.
